0.body: Welcome to the Snowflake Terraform Infrastructure documentation. This project provides a comprehensive Infrastructure-as-Code (IaC) solution for managing Snowflake resources using Terraform.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: This Terraform configuration manages Snowflake infrastructure components through a modular architecture: Roles Module : Account roles with hierarchical relationships Users Module : Person users, service users, and legacy service users Warehouse Module : Compute warehouses with configurable sizing and scaling policies Database Module : Snowflake databases with retention policies and automatic privilege grants Schema Module : Database schemas with managed access and automatic privilege grants Tables Module : Structured data tables with columns, constraints, and automatic privilege grants Views Module : SQL views for data aggregation and presentation with automatic privilege grants All modules handle privilege grants internally, providing a complete, self-contained infrastructure management solution.

124.body: This document explains the modular architecture of the Terraform project and how modules interact.
124.title: Module Architecture

125.body: The project uses a fully modular architecture with seven main modules: Roles Module : Manages Snowflake account roles Users Module : Manages Snowflake users Warehouse Module : Manages Snowflake warehouses Database Module : Manages Snowflake databases with automatic grants Schema Module : Manages Snowflake schemas with automatic grants Tables Module : Manages Snowflake tables with automatic grants Views Module : Manages Snowflake views with automatic grants

127.body: Each module has a single, well-defined responsibility: Roles Module : Only manages roles and role grants Users Module : Only manages users and user-role assignments Warehouse Module : Only manages warehouses and warehouse privileges

78.body: main.tf The primary configuration file containing: Module declarations for all resources (roles, users, warehouses, databases, schemas, tables, views) All resources are managed through modules - no direct resource definitions Each module handles its own privilege grants automatically Map-based configuration for each module (role_map, user_map, warehouse_map, database_map, schema_map, table_map, view_map) provider.tf Defines the Terraform providers: Snowflake provider configuration Provider aliases for different roles (SECURITYADMIN, SYSADMIN) Required provider versions variables.tf Defines all input variables: Snowflake connection parameters Default values Variable types and descriptions outputs.tf Defines outputs from the root module: Module outputs Resource references Sensitive output flags terraform.tfvars Contains actual variable values: Not committed to version control (in .gitignore) Contains sensitive credentials (snowflake_password, etc.) Environment-specific values Required variables: snowflake_organization, snowflake_account, snowflake_username, snowflake_password, snowflake_role, snowflake_warehouse imported_resources.md Documents resources that have been imported into Terraform management: Tracks imported resources for reference Contains import commands for future use Helps maintain awareness of manually imported resources README.md Project README file: Instructions for building mdBook documentation Quick start guide Project overview book.toml mdBook configuration file: Defines book title, description, and metadata Configures HTML output settings Sets search and theme preferences
78.title: Root Level Files

79.body: The project uses a fully modular architecture with seven main modules: modules/snowflake/roles/ Manages Snowflake account roles: Creates roles with hierarchical relationships Grants roles to parent roles Outputs role information modules/snowflake/users/ Manages Snowflake users: Supports person users, service users, and legacy service users Assigns roles to users Configures user defaults (warehouse, role) modules/snowflake/warehouse/ Manages Snowflake warehouses: Creates warehouses with configurable properties Grants warehouse privileges to roles automatically Supports multiple warehouse configurations modules/snowflake/database/ Manages Snowflake databases: Creates databases with retention policies Grants database privileges to roles automatically Supports multiple databases with different configurations modules/snowflake/schema/ Manages Snowflake schemas: Creates schemas within databases Supports managed access and transient schemas Grants schema privileges to roles automatically modules/snowflake/tables/ Manages Snowflake tables: Creates tables with column definitions Supports various data types and constraints Grants table privileges to roles automatically modules/snowflake/views/ Manages Snowflake views: Creates views with SQL statements Supports table references in SQL Grants view privileges to roles automatically
79.title: Module Structure

85.body:
The following dependency order is enforced: Roles 
Warehouses (references roles for grants) 
Users (references roles and warehouses) 
Databases (references roles for grants) 
Schemas (references databases and roles for grants) 
Tables (references databases, schemas, and roles for grants) 
Views (references databases, schemas, tables, and roles for grants) Note: All grants are handled automatically within each module, so there are no separate grant resources in the root configuration. Each module manages its own privilege grants internally.
